A slighty high number of men believe abortion is for their wives’ health/ wellbeing, but not for their own.^6 Men’s approval of abortion also seems to have some link to the chances of an abortion actually being performed in a country. In Bangladesh abortion is legally restricted, and in India there is a requirement to obtain written consent of a responsible relative, and both of these countries have a largely unwelcoming attitude from men towards abortion.

However in Nepal and Sri Lanka where abortion has been decriminalised, 58% of men believe that abortion should be a personal choice. As countries with low levels of abortion, these countries represent an important situation in which the role that male opinion plays in low access to abortion could effectively be remedied.

Gender roles, power, and abortion law

Due to the generally patriarchal structure of many countries worldwide, debates over abortion and women’s role in society often dominate political discourse. This can in turn result in abortion control.

The limitations that women in many countries face in exercising their right to abortion speak to the impact that gender norms have upon access to abortion and where regulations situate women within wider gender roles.

The opinion of male family members and elders, as well as their self-perception, relates in part to the wider societal attitudes towards abortion.

Lotus blossom, the symbol of royalty and sexual innocence, bursts forth from a politically repressive society.

Law reforms, power and authority
